options.explanation:
When two or more parallel lines are cut by a transversal:

![parallel lines, transversals](web+graphie://ka-perseus-graphie.s3.amazonaws.com/4262db5f8009fdd2d0973e0fc44ccac2167868d2)

- Their *corresponding* angles are *equal*.

$\begin{align}
\purpleC{\angle{1}}=\purpleC{\angle{5}}, \phantom{x}\purpleC{\angle{3}}=\purpleC{\angle{7}},\phantom{x}\maroonD{\angle{2}}=\maroonD{\angle{6}}, \text{and}\phantom{x}\maroonD{\angle{4}}=\maroonD{\angle{8}}
\end{align}$

- Their *alternate interior/exterior* angles are *equal*.

$\begin{align}
\purpleC{\angle{3}}=\purpleC{\angle{5}}, \phantom{x}\purpleC{\angle{1}}=\purpleC{\angle{7}},\phantom{x}\maroonD{\angle{2}}=\maroonD{\angle{8}}, \text{and}\phantom{x}\maroonD{\angle{4}}=\maroonD{\angle{6}}
\end{align}$

- Each pair of *interior/exterior angles* on *same side* of the transversal are *supplementary*.

$\begin{align}
\purpleC{\angle{3}}+\maroonD{\angle{6}}=180\degree, \phantom{x}\purpleC{\angle{5}}+\maroonD{\angle{4}}=180\degree\\\\
\phantom{x}\purpleC{\angle{7}}+\maroonD{\angle{2}}=180\degree, \phantom{x}\purpleC{\angle{1}}+\maroonD{\angle{8}}=180\degree
\end{align}$

